 With regard to the new OSP Harris said &quot; If we do not have a crew escape system in there- then shame on us. We need to make sure that the next generation vehicle is based not on probability but on 'assurability'.<br>
 Harris added later &quot;We need to use the best technology we can to assure that the crew survives. If we cannot do it in Shuttle then need to have that in next vehicle . If we do not do this now - and do some soul searching - we will be in the same place 20-30 years from now.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They're talking about flying the Shuttle as a &quot;heavy cargo lifter&quot;<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
They're in complete denial that the Shuttle isn't good at crew <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">or</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> cargo... It's a flying (or not flying) garbage can -or maybe what's inside the can...<br>
<br>
Tear out all the crew environment stuff: walls, floors, air system, toilets, seats, controls and all. Build in a 4-person crew pod which is full envelope, and you might have a useful medium lift vehicle, but it won't support extensive EVA or have lots of on-orbit time, because you've got to dispense with all that to let people survive the thing, and lift any cargo.<br>
<br>
See this also<br>
